+---
+title: Execution patterns
+description: How queue-level execution patterns (static-dag, pipeline, map-reduce) layer above the engine tick loop — pattern config, the gate/respawn circle-back, extendRun + run.extended audit entries, and the forward-arc-never-rewind invariant.
+---
+
+The core orchestrator engine is deliberately narrow: it schedules a fixed DAG,
+polls running items via reconcile, and moves each item through a defined status
+lattice. That model covers a large class of work, but some jobs are structurally
+dynamic — the exact set of items is only knowable once earlier items run. Rather
+than complicate the engine, agora layers **execution patterns** on top of it: a
+per-queue strategy object that observes terminal items after each tick and may
+answer with new work to add to the same run.
+
+For the tick loop that patterns plug into, see
+[How an offload run executes](/agora/explanation/how-offload-runs/). For the
+shape of a plan, see the [plan.json reference](/agora/reference/plan-json/). This
+page is about what happens *above* the engine between ticks.
+
+## What an execution pattern is
+
+An execution pattern is a pure, stateless strategy object registered on a queue.
+It is not a new trigger, a separate queue, or a parallel scheduler — it is a
+**post-tick hook** on a single queue. After the engine tick for that queue
+finishes, the orchestrator runs a **pattern phase**:
+
+1. Collect every unsealed run on the queue.
+2. For each terminal item in the run, call `pattern.onTaskDone(item, ctx)` — a
+   pure function that receives a single `ItemState` plus a `PatternContext`
+   containing the full `runItems` list.
+3. If `onTaskDone` returns a non-null spawn directive, apply it through the
+   audited `extendRun` seam.
+4. Check whether the run has settled and the pattern has no more spawns to issue;
+   if yes, seal the run. A run that just received new items cannot seal in the
+   same pattern phase.
+
+Because patterns are pure and keep no state of their own, the same `onTaskDone`
+call is safe to repeat after a crash — the spawn directive is derived fresh from
+the run's current item set every time.
+
+## Queue-level pattern config
+
+Patterns are registered per-queue via `AgoraOrchestratorOptions`. A queue without
+a `pattern` entry uses the engine's default behavior — a static DAG submitted at
+`agora orch submit` time and never extended; the pattern phase is bypassed
+entirely for that queue.
+
+```ts
+import { mapReduce, pipeline } from '@agora/orchestrator';
+
+const orchestrator = new AgoraOrchestrator({
+  queues: {
+    default: { concurrency: 4 },
+    etl:    { concurrency: 8, pattern: mapReduce },
+    review: { concurrency: 2, pattern: pipeline },
+  },
+});
+```
+
+Three pattern types ship with the orchestrator:
+
+| Pattern | When to use |
+|---|---|
+| `static-dag` | The full item graph is known at submit time. Pass this pattern to opt into explicit pattern machinery without enabling dynamic spawning; a queue with no `pattern` set is equivalent at runtime but bypasses the pattern phase entirely. |
+| `pipeline` | A sequence of named stages where a gate item may fail and a later stage may circle back to retry from an earlier point. |
+| `map-reduce` | A splitter item emits a variable-length list of keys via its `outputRefs`, and the pattern spawns one mapper item per key, then a single reducer after all mappers finish with status `done`. |
+
+Map-reduce item roles are not configured at the queue level — executor names and
+other spawn parameters are declared on the splitter item itself under
+`inputs.mapReduce` (with shape `{ map: { executor, ... }, reduce: { executor, ... } }`).
+
+## The gate/respawn circle-back
+
+A **gate** is a pipeline stage item whose job is to inspect the output of the
+preceding stage and decide whether the run should continue, retry, or abort. A
+gate that succeeds unblocks the next stage as a normal `depends_on` edge. A gate
+that fails is where the circle-back mechanic applies.
+
+When a gate item reaches `failed` and the pipeline pattern's retry budget is not
+yet exhausted, the pattern's `onTaskDone` call returns a **respawn directive**.
+The stage to retry from is the `subject` declared in the gate's `inputs.gate`
+config. The directive produces three kinds of new items:
+
+- A **fix item** (`${base}-fix-${attempt}`, e.g. `review-gate-fix-1`) that
+  `depends_on` the original subject item. The gate's `reason` string is merged
+  into the fix item's `inputs` as `gateReason`.
+- A **gate copy** (`${base}~${next}`, e.g. `review-gate~2`) whose `depends_on`
+  edges are remapped through a substitution map so they point at the fix item.
+- Copies of any skipped downstream items (`${descendant}~${next}`), with
+  `depends_on` edges similarly remapped.
+
+The failed gate branch stays in the run as sealed history — its status is
+`failed` and it never becomes `done`.
+
+From the engine's perspective nothing special happens: `extendRun` appends new
+items whose `depends_on` edges are all already terminal `done` items or freshly
+added items in the same directive, so they immediately become `ready` on the next
+tick's ready phase and proceed normally. The pattern has produced a second arc
+through the same logical stages without touching any already-finished work.
+
+A practical example: a `lint` stage produces a patch, a `review-gate` inspects
+it (with `inputs.gate.subject: lint`), finds a style violation, and fails. The
+pattern spawns a `review-gate-fix-1` item (with `gateReason` from the gate's
+failure reason, and `depends_on: [lint]`) and a `review-gate~2` gate copy whose
+`depends_on` is remapped to point at the fix item. If `review-gate~2` passes, the
+pipeline proceeds. If the retry budget is exhausted, the run settles as `failed`
+and no more spawns are issued.
+
+```mermaid
+stateDiagram-v2
+  direction LR
+  [*] --> lint
+  lint --> review_gate
+  review_gate --> done: pass
+  review_gate --> review_gate_fix_1: fail + retry budget > 0\n(extendRun respawn)
+  review_gate_fix_1 --> review_gate_2
+  review_gate_2 --> done: pass
+  review_gate_2 --> failed: budget exhausted
+```
+
+The `review_gate` node above stays `failed` in the run forever — the diagram
+shows logical flow, not a status transition.
+
+## extendRun and the run.extended audit entry
+
+All dynamic item addition goes through a single audited seam: `extendRun`. This
+is not a backdoor around the engine — it is the same `validateRun` call that
+`submitRun` uses, applied to the *merged* graph (existing items plus proposed
+new items). If the merged graph would be invalid — a dependency on a
+non-existent item, a cycle, a duplicate id — the spawn is rejected and the
+pattern's directive is dropped as if it returned null.
+
+When `extendRun` succeeds it persists the new items, then appends a `run.extended`
+audit entry on a best-effort basis:
+
+```json
+{
+  "kind": "run.extended",
+  "runId": "etl-run-20260607",
+  "actor": "pattern:etl",
+  "itemId": "splitter",
+  "at": "2026-06-07T03:41:02.114Z"
+}
+```
+
+`actor` is always `pattern:<queueName>` — the pattern acted, not a human.
+`itemId` names the terminal item whose outputs triggered the spawn. The audit
+append is best-effort: a failure during append is silently swallowed while the
+items remain in the store.
+
+The `agora verify` provenance check treats the full merged graph as canonical and
+traces lineage through the `run.extended` audit entries, which record the cause
+item that triggered each extension. Every dynamically added item is traceable to
+the cause item that drove its creation.
+
+## The forward-arc-never-rewind invariant
+
+The central safety property of dynamic spawning is simple: **spawned items may
+only `depends_on` items that already exist in the run at spawn time.** Patterns
+cannot express a dependency on an item that does not yet exist, and they cannot
+modify an item that is already in the run. The graph grows forward; it never
+mutates backward.
+
+This invariant is enforced by `validateRun` on the merged graph:
+
+- Every id in any item's `depends_on` must resolve to an item present in the
+  merged item list before the transaction commits. A `depends_on` that names
+  a not-yet-spawned future item fails validation and the whole directive is
+  rejected.
+- Item ids must be unique across the merged graph. Patterns that generate
+  deterministic ids are idempotent: a re-run of `onTaskDone` after a crash
+  re-derives the same ids; `extendRun` finds them already present and returns
+  early before any validation or write.
+
+Three consequences follow from the invariant:
+
+**No cycles, ever.** Because spawned items only point backward, there is no way
+to construct a cycle through `extendRun`. The DAG stays a DAG across every spawn,
+and the engine's dependency resolver requires no cycle-detection on the hot path.
+
+**Circle-back is new lineage, not rewind.** The "respawn from stage N" pattern
+described above does not re-run or mutate stage N's original item — it appends a
+new fix item that `depends_on` the original subject, and a new gate copy that
+depends on the fix. The failed arc is permanent sealed history;
+`agora verify` will always report that `review-gate` failed. The new arc's
+provenance is fully separate.
+
+**Settled state is monotone.** An item that reaches a terminal status
+(`done`, `failed`, `skipped`, `cancelled`) never changes status. Patterns
+observe terminal items but cannot un-terminal them. A run's sealed history is
+therefore append-only: `run.extended` entries accumulate; they never revise.
+
+Together these properties mean the orchestrator's audit guarantees extend to
+dynamically grown runs without special-casing: `agora verify` treats the full
+merged graph as the canonical graph and checks provenance closure over it.
+
+## Replay safety and determinism
+
+Because `onTaskDone` is a pure function with no external state, patterns are
+replay-safe by construction. If the orchestrator crashes after persisting new
+items but before the next tick, the next startup's pattern phase re-runs
+`onTaskDone` for the same terminal items, derives the same spawn directive, calls
+`extendRun` again, and returns early with no writes — the ids already exist. No
+items are duplicated, no audit entries are doubled.
+
+Spawn id determinism is the pattern author's responsibility, not the engine's.
+The built-in `map-reduce` pattern derives mapper ids as `map-${k}` where `k` is
+the raw sorted output key from the splitter's `outputRefs`, so they are stable
+across re-inspections. Custom patterns should follow the same convention: compute
+ids from the cause item's outputs, not from a process-global counter or
+wall-clock time.
